 This holds essentially due to the fact that the closed quotient \mathcal {I}/\mathcal {O}_{X} is a geometric construction. By the dual statement of Lemma , the following is a coequaliser in \mathrm {Sh}(X), 

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
  \{ a,b \in  \mathcal {O}_{X} \mid  \exists  i\in \mathcal {I}.\, a \vee  i = b \vee  i \} \ar [r, shift left] \ar [r, shift right] & \mathcal  O_{X} \ar [r, two heads] & \mathcal  I/\mathcal  O
  \end {tikzcd}


Since the stalk functor (-)_x is the inverse image of a geometric morphism, it preserves geometric formulas and coequalisers. It follows that we have a coequaliser 

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
  \{ a,b \in  \mathcal {O}_{X,x} \mid  \exists  i\in \mathcal {I}_x.\, a \vee  i = b \vee  i \} \ar [r, shift left] \ar [r, shift right] & \mathcal  O_{X,x} \ar [r, two heads] & (\mathcal  I/\mathcal  O)_x
  \end {tikzcd}


which implies (\mathcal {I}/\mathcal {O}_{X})_x \cong  \mathcal {I}_x/\mathcal {O}_{X,x}.

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Let X be a locally distributed space, and \mathcal {I} a sheaf of ideal of \mathcal {O}_{X}. We define the subset of X
 C_{\mathcal {I}} := \{x \in  X\mid 1 \not \in  \mathcal {I}_x\} 
Equivalently, x\in  C_{\mathcal {I}} iff the stalk (\mathcal {I}/\mathcal {O}_{X})_x of the quotient distributive lattice at x is non-trivial. This is a closed set, since if 0 = 1 inÂ (\mathcal {I}/\mathcal {O}_{X})_x, then 0=1 in an open neighbourhood of x.
